{"title_page": "Newspaper riddle", "text_new": "[[File:2012_newspaper_reader_Santa_Cruz_Argentina_7133646327.jpg|thumb|A black and white newspaper that is \"read.\"]]\nThe '''newspaper riddle''' is a [[riddle joke]] or conundrum that begins with the question:<ref name=Barrick>{{cite journal|title=The Newspaper Riddle Joke|author=Mac E. Barrick|journal=The Journal of American Folklore|volume=87|issue=345|date=July\u2013September 1974|pages=253&ndash;257|doi=10.2307/538740}}</ref>\n:'''Q''': What is black and white and red all over?\nThe traditional answer, which relies upon the [[homophone|identical pronunciation]] of the words \"[[wikt:red|red]]\" and \"[[wikt:read|read]]\", is:<ref name=Barrick /><ref>{{cite book|title=The Study of Language|author=George Yule|year=1996|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-56851-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/studyoflanguage00yule_1/page/122 122]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/studyoflanguage00yule_1}}</ref>\n:'''A''': A [[newspaper]]\n\nBarrick<ref name=Barrick /> believes this riddle to be \"perhaps the most common example of a folk riddle collected in the United States in the twentieth century\", pointing out that between 1917 and 1939 it appeared in 15 collections of folk riddles, and in a further six between 1939 and 1974.\n\nAlternative answers to the riddle exist, where red is used as a color, parodying the canonical form of the riddle. Examples include: \"a chocolate sundae with ketchup on top\", \"a badger in a blender\", and \"a crossword done in red ink\".<ref>{{cite book|title=New York Folklore Quarterly|author=New York Folklore Society|year=1945|publisher=Cornell University Press|page=247}}</ref>  Portnoy describes these answers as \"adequate, but not clever\", because they lack the homophonic pun.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Remnant: Essays on a Theme in Old English Verse|author=Phyllis Portnoy|page=32|year=2006|publisher=Runetree|isbn=1-898-57710-2}}</ref>\n\nA much darker version of the riddle exists with the answer \"A Wounded Nun.\" This is also the answer to the similar riddle \"What's black and white and crawls on all fours?\" <ref name=\"Oring2010\">{{cite book|author=Elliott Oring|title=Engaging Humor|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b2T72z_bawcC&pg=PA24|date=1 October 2010|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-09205-3|pages=24\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Translations==\n\nIn ''The Language of Jokes'', Delia Chiaro notes that it is, technically, [[Untranslatability|impossible to translate]] this joke into languages other than English, pointing out that, for example, in [[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], and [[German language|German]] the words \"[[wikt:rouge|rouge]]\", \"[[wikt:rosso|rosso]]\", and \"[[wikt:rot|rot]]\" have no meaning other than \"red\" and do not possess homophones.<ref name=Chiaro>{{cite book|title=The Language of Jokes: analysing verbal play|author=Delia Chiaro|pages=[https://archive.org/details/languageofjokesa0000chia/page/92 92&ndash;93]|year=1992|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-03090-0|url=https://archive.org/details/languageofjokesa0000chia/page/92}}</ref>\n\nShe adds that it is possible to translate the intent of the joke, and to retain the invariant core of the colour red and the reference to a newspaper, by substituting a different riddle that relies upon metaphor, albeit that the homophonic play upon words is lost.  She gives the following example in French, which relies upon the facts that ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'' is the newspaper of the [[French Communist Party]], and that, as \"red\" has in English, \"[[wikt:rouge|rouge]]\" in French has political connotations of Communism:<ref name=Chiaro />\n:'''Q''': Qu'est-ce qui/Quel journal est tout rouge et noir et blanc?\n:'''A''': ''L'Humanit\u00e9''\n\nShe also gives a similar example in Italian, this time using the newspaper of the [[Italian Communist Party]] ([[L'Unit\u00e0]]), noting that in Italian the order of black and white is the reverse of that in English, since \"nero e bianco\" is a marked form,{{Explain|date=August 2019}} and that for prosodic naturalness \"rosso\" must come first:<ref name=Chiaro />\n:'''Q''': Quale giornale \u00e8 rosso, bianco e nero?\n:'''A''': ''L'Unit\u00e0''\n\nFor German, she gives this example, which again, like Italian, requires the colour adjectives to be in a different order:<ref name=Chiaro />\n:'''Q''': Was ist rot, schwarz und weiss?\n:'''A''': ''[[Die Tageszeitung]]''\n\n==Famous uses==\n\nIn 2009, Jason Jones pitched this riddle to Bill Keller, the editor of The New York Times, giving the answer: \"Your balance sheet\".<ref>[http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/wed-june-10-2009/end-times End Times - The Daily Show with Jon Stewart - 06/10/09 - Video Clip | Comedy Central<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n \nJimmy Kimmel at the 2012 White House Correspondent's Dinner did this joke and replied: \"Nothing anymore\", in an allusion to the death of print news.<ref>Jimmy Kimmel at the White House Correspondent's Dinner- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pazhvZ-FnNg</ref>\n\n== What goes black and and white black and white a cow  rolling down a hill ==\n* [[Elephant joke]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Jokes]]\n[[Category:Newspapers]]\n[[Cskekskwkak@zks,s,kwategory:Riddles]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:2012_newspaper_reader_Santa_Cruz_Argentina_7133646327.jpg|thumb|A black and white newspaper that is \"read.\"]]\nThe '''newspaper riddle''' is a [[riddle joke]] or conundrum that begins with the question:<ref name=Barrick>{{cite journal|title=The Newspaper Riddle Joke|author=Mac E. Barrick|journal=The Journal of American Folklore|volume=87|issue=345|date=July\u2013September 1974|pages=253&ndash;257|doi=10.2307/538740}}</ref>\n:'''Q''': What is black and white and red all over?\nThe traditional answer, which relies upon the [[homophone|identical pronunciation]] of the words \"[[wikt:red|red]]\" and \"[[wikt:read|read]]\", is:<ref name=Barrick /><ref>{{cite book|title=The Study of Language|author=George Yule|year=1996|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-56851-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/studyoflanguage00yule_1/page/122 122]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/studyoflanguage00yule_1}}</ref>\n:'''A''': A [[newspaper]]\n\nBarrick<ref name=Barrick /> believes this riddle to be \"perhaps the most common example of a folk riddle collected in the United States in the twentieth century\", pointing out that between 1917 and 1939 it appeared in 15 collections of folk riddles, and in a further six between 1939 and 1974.\n\nAlternative answers to the riddle exist, where red is used as a color, parodying the canonical form of the riddle. Examples include: \"a chocolate sundae with ketchup on top\", \"a badger in a blender\", and \"a crossword done in red ink\".<ref>{{cite book|title=New York Folklore Quarterly|author=New York Folklore Society|year=1945|publisher=Cornell University Press|page=247}}</ref>  Portnoy describes these answers as \"adequate, but not clever\", because they lack the homophonic pun.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Remnant: Essays on a Theme in Old English Verse|author=Phyllis Portnoy|page=32|year=2006|publisher=Runetree|isbn=1-898-57710-2}}</ref>\n\nA much darker version of the riddle exists with the answer \"A Wounded Nun.\" This is also the answer to the similar riddle \"What's black and white and crawls on all fours?\" <ref name=\"Oring2010\">{{cite book|author=Elliott Oring|title=Engaging Humor|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b2T72z_bawcC&pg=PA24|date=1 October 2010|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-09205-3|pages=24\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Translations==\n\nIn ''The Language of Jokes'', Delia Chiaro notes that it is, technically, [[Untranslatability|impossible to translate]] this joke into languages other than English, pointing out that, for example, in [[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], and [[German language|German]] the words \"[[wikt:rouge|rouge]]\", \"[[wikt:rosso|rosso]]\", and \"[[wikt:rot|rot]]\" have no meaning other than \"red\" and do not possess homophones.<ref name=Chiaro>{{cite book|title=The Language of Jokes: analysing verbal play|author=Delia Chiaro|pages=[https://archive.org/details/languageofjokesa0000chia/page/92 92&ndash;93]|year=1992|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-03090-0|url=https://archive.org/details/languageofjokesa0000chia/page/92}}</ref>\n\nShe adds that it is possible to translate the intent of the joke, and to retain the invariant core of the colour red and the reference to a newspaper, by substituting a different riddle that relies upon metaphor, albeit that the homophonic play upon words is lost.  She gives the following example in French, which relies upon the facts that ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'' is the newspaper of the [[French Communist Party]], and that, as \"red\" has in English, \"[[wikt:rouge|rouge]]\" in French has political connotations of Communism:<ref name=Chiaro />\n:'''Q''': Qu'est-ce qui/Quel journal est tout rouge et noir et blanc?\n:'''A''': ''L'Humanit\u00e9''\n\nShe also gives a similar example in Italian, this time using the newspaper of the [[Italian Communist Party]] ([[L'Unit\u00e0]]), noting that in Italian the order of black and white is the reverse of that in English, since \"nero e bianco\" is a marked form,{{Explain|date=August 2019}} and that for prosodic naturalness \"rosso\" must come first:<ref name=Chiaro />\n:'''Q''': Quale giornale \u00e8 rosso, bianco e nero?\n:'''A''': ''L'Unit\u00e0''\n\nFor German, she gives this example, which again, like Italian, requires the colour adjectives to be in a different order:<ref name=Chiaro />\n:'''Q''': Was ist rot, schwarz und weiss?\n:'''A''': ''[[Die Tageszeitung]]''\n\n==Famous uses==\n\nIn 2009, Jason Jones pitched this riddle to Bill Keller, the editor of The New York Times, giving the answer: \"Your balance sheet\".<ref>[http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/wed-june-10-2009/end-times End Times - The Daily Show with Jon Stewart - 06/10/09 - Video Clip | Comedy Central<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n \nJimmy Kimmel at the 2012 White House Correspondent's Dinner did this joke and replied: \"Nothing anymore\", in an allusion to the death of print news.<ref>Jimmy Kimmel at the White House Correspondent's Dinner- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pazhvZ-FnNg</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Elephant joke]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Jokes]]\n[[Category:Newspapers]]\n[[Category:Riddles]]\n", "name_user": "99.23.7.37", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newspaper_riddle"}
{"title_page": "Forts in Sri Lanka", "text_new": "{{Forts in Sri Lanka map}}\n\n'''[[Fort]]s and [[fortification]]s in [[Sri Lanka]]''' date back thousands of years with many being built by Sri Lankan Kings, these include several walled cities. With the out set of colonial rule in the [[Indian Ocean]], Sri Lanka was occupied by several major colonial empires that from time-to-time became the dominant power in the Indian Ocean. The colonists built several western styled forts, mostly in and round the coast of the island. The first to build colonial forts in Sri Lanka were the [[Portugal|Portuguese]], these forts were captured and later expanded by the [[Netherlands|Dutch]]. The [[United Kingdom|British]] occupied these  Dutch forts during the [[Napoleonic wars]].\n\nMost of colonial forts were garrisoned up until the early 20th century. The coastal forts had [[coastal artillery]] manned by the [[Ceylon Garrison Artillery]] during the two world wars. Most of these were abandoned by the military, but retained civil administrative officers, while others retained military garrisons, which were more administrative than operational. Some were reoccupied by military units with the escalation of the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]], Jaffna fort for example came under siege several times.\n{{clear}}\n\n== Ancient forts ==\n{| style=\"text-align:center; width:100%\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Name !! Founded !! Abandoned !! Location !! Condition !! Controlled by !! Type !! Notes\n|-\n|  || [[Vijithapura]] || 5th Century BC<br />[[Anuradhapura Kingdom]] ||  || [[Central Province, Sri Lanka|Central Province]]  ||  ||  || Fortress City || <ref group=\"N\">It was the site of a [[Battle of Vijithapura|major battle]] between the forces of [[Ellalan]] and [[Dutthagamani]]</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Senaveratna|first=John M. |title=The story of the Sinhalese from the most ancient times up to the end of \"the Mahavansa\" or Great dynasty: Vijaya to Maha Sena, B.C. 543 to A.D.302|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=1997|pages=125\u2013128|isbn=978-81-206-1271-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X9TeEcMi0e0C&pg=PA124#v=onepage&q=}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Sigiriya.jpg|100px]] || [[Sigiriya]] || 5th Century<br />by [[Kashyapa I of Anuradhapura|Kashyapa I]] || 495 CE || [[Dambulla]], [[Central Province, Sri Lanka|Central Province]] || Ruined || [[Government of Sri Lanka]] || [[Citadel]] || <ref group=\"N\">Royal Palace. Briefly used as an outpost of the [[Kingdom of Kandy]] in the 16th and 17th centuries.</ref>\n|-\n|  || [[Mapagala fortress]] ||  ||  || [[Central Province, Sri Lanka|Central Province]] ||  ||  ||  || <ref group=\"N\">Located to the south of [[Sigiriya]] is the Mapagala Fortress (\u2018Rock of the Viceroy\u2019), a fortress with massive stone walls, which was built prior to Sigiriya.</ref>\n|-\n|  || [[Balana fort]] ||  ||  || [[Balana]], [[Central Province, Sri Lanka|Central Province]] ||  ||  ||  ||\n|-\n|  || [[Sitawaka fort]] ||  ||  || [[Avissawella]], [[Western Province, Sri Lanka|Western Province]]  ||  ||  ||  ||\n|}\n\n== Colonial forts ==\n=== Portuguese forts ===\n{| style=\"text-align:center; width:100%\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Name !! Founded !! Abandoned !! Location !! Condition !! Controlled by !! Type !! Notes\n|-\n|  || [[Fort (Colombo)|Colombo fort]] || 1518, 1554 || 1524, 1870 || [[Fort (Colombo)|Colombo fort]], [[Western Province, Sri Lanka|Western Province]] || Destroyed || - || Defence ||\n|-\n| [[File:Fort Fredrick05.jpg|100px]] || [[Fort Fredrick]] || 1624 || - || [[Trincomalee]], [[Eastern Province, Sri Lanka|Eastern Province]] || Good || [[Government of Sri Lanka]] || Defence || <ref group=\"N\">Later controlled by the Dutch and then the British</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Batticaloa Portuguese (dutch) fort.jpg|100px]] || [[Batticaloa fort]] || 1628 ||  || [[Batticaloa]], [[Eastern Province, Sri Lanka|Eastern Province]] || Good || [[Government of Sri Lanka]] || Defence || <ref gr